data.value:
Welcome to DynamicWorkflow !
DynamicWorkflow is an easy and powerful tool to create simple workflows for Microsoft Dynamic Link Libraries (DLL). It supports all managed-mode .NET 2.0 and higher based files.
- USER INTERFACE -
User interface is divided into 3 columns, each of the columns contains different information: • Repository (Left) - Contains current opened repository (single directory) - Contains information about currently selected node • Work area (Center) - Text window to write custom workflows - Execution console (displays errors and method results) • Memory (Right) - Virtually allocated memory and contents - Application statistics
- GETTING STARTED -
To start creating your own workflow, you need to open a repository directory. You do this by opening File menu and selecting Open -> DLL Repository option. Library files from choosen directory are automatically scanned and loaded into repository tree. Files not compiled by .NET framework are automatically skipped.
- METHODS -
Once you have more than one method in repository, you can start with executing method by selecting a method (third level node in tree) and selecting Run -> Run Method from Top menu. Same action can be achieved by double clicking on method.
Single method dialog appears and you can set method parameters, either from stored memory or custom values. Select correct parameter and enter value. If method returns a value, you can choose to what location it will be saved.
You can run the method with clicking Run Method button. Method is executed in virtual machine and result is shown in the Execution console. Value in memory also changes based on your settings.
If you wish to add the execution of selected method to your Workflow, click Add to Workflow button and method call script will be inserted into currently active Workflow at cursor position.
- WORKFLOWS -
The advantage of this tool is connecting methods by sending output from one method as input parameter into another. You can achieve this with Workflows. You can have opened as many as you like at same time.
Enter your Workflow script into large text window, or open existing Workflow by choosing File then Open -> Workflow in the Top menu.
To execute your Workflow, choose Run -> Run Workflow option in Top menu.
- MEMORY -
To make methods work and interact with each other, memory is required. You have 17 blocks of memory allocated by default, if you require more for your workflow, select File -> Settings option in Top menu and change the value.
Warning: if you reduce your memory size, memory cells beyond choosen point are deallocated and your data in those cells is lost.
You can also enter values directly into the memory by selecting Edit -> Store var in memory option in Top menu or you can erase whole memory with Edit -> Clear memory option.
If you desire you can create memory dump at any time with selecting File -> Save As ... -> Memory dump option. Memory can later be restored with File -> Open ... -> Memory dump option in Top menu.
- SCRIPTING -
Application contains a small scripting engine built with purpoise to create powerful Workflows. It does not support nested functions and expressions. It has 2 predefined functions:
• Memory (Int32) - Accesses memory at location • Store (Int32, Type, Value) - Stores value of type into location
Supported types for Store function: Boolean, Byte, SByte, Char, Decimal, Double, Single, Int32, UInt32, Int64, UInt64, Int16, UInt16, String
Examples: Memory (5) = Class.Method (); -> Return object from Class.Method () will be stored into Memory cell 5. Class.Method (Memory (3)); -> Method Class.Method () will be executed with parameter in Memory cell 5.
Store (4, Int32, 55); -> Stores Int32 with value 55 into Memory cell 4.
Each command requires semicolon to define the end. Strings must be encapsed with double quotes ("), delimiter is \ by default.
Methods can be drag and dropped from repository into desired place in Workflow, same with Memory function from Memory list in the far-right side.
- ABOUT AUTHOR -
